SIMPLE: supervenient
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Supervenient
<hw>Su`per*ven"ient</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>superveniens</ets>, p. pr.]</ety> <def>Coming as something
additional or extraneous; coming afterwards.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That branch of belief was in him <qex>supervenient</qex> to
Christian practice.</q> <rj><qau>Hammond.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Divorces can be granted, <qex>a mensa et toro</qex>, only for
<qex>supervenient</qex> causes.</q> <rj><qau>Z. Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Supervention</ent>⟦br⟧
